NHANES Diabetes Patient Data¶

by Christopher Phillips¶

Investigation Overview¶

The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) is a program of studies designed to assess the health and nutritional status of adults and children in the United States.

The goal of this analysis is to examine patient Diabetes and associated patient related comorbidities.

Dataset Overview¶

The NHANES interview includes demographic, socioeconomic, dietary, and health-related questions. The examination component consists of medical, dental, and physiological measurements, as well as laboratory tests administered by highly trained medical personnel.

Distribution of Patient Age¶

The distribution of patients by age leans heavily towards children with the adults capped at 80.

Distribution of BMI¶

BMI is a combination of Weight To Height. BMI Index 25 to 30 is considered over weight. 30 and above is considered to be obese.
The patient data set indicates that there is a positive correlation between weight/BMI and rising A1C.

Distribution of GlycoHemoglobin (A1C)¶

Diabetes is measured by patient average blood sugar levels called GLycoHemoglobin. Patients without diabetes average 5.6 and below. Between 5.7 and 6.3 are considered to be prediabetes. 6.4 and above are considered to have diabetes.

A1C and Diastolic/Systolic Blood Pressure¶

The correlation with Systolic Blood Pressure, is slightly higher than with Diastolic Blood Pressure. Systolic measures the stiffness in the arteries. Diastolic measure more of the heart when it's at rest between pumps.

A1C and Weight and Gender¶

A1C and Weight have a positive correlation between each other. This chart also exams the data by Gender.

High Density Lipoprotein (HDL), Low Density Lipoprotein (LDL) Cholesterols and Weight and Gender¶

HDL has a negative correlation with Diabetes, which LDL has a positive correlation with Diabetes. This chart also exams the data by Gender and Adulthood status.

A1C and Triglycerides¶

High triglycerides doesn't lead to diabetes, but their levels indicate that the system for turning food into energy isn't working properly. Normally, your body makes insulin, which escorts glucose -- the type of sugar in your blood --inside your cells. There, your body turns glucose into energy. The data shows a positive correlation between diabetes and triglycerides.

Charts indicate a positive relationship between Triglycerides and Diabetes.

Data Set Parameters Correlation¶

The correlation map shows mathematically how the parameters relate to each other. Age, Weight/BMI, Triglycerides, and Systolic Blood Pressure have a positive correlation with Diabetes. There are insignificant correlations between Cholesterol and Diastolic Blood Pressure and Diabetes.
